				\begin{document}$$\mathrm {SrTiO}_3$$\end{document} from Table 2 with g2=0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathrm {g}_2=0$$\end{document} are chosen in order to verify our 2D model with the reduced-order beam formulation from Deng et al. [34] where the ratio L/W/h are fixed to be 20/1/1 for all values of thickness h. The results are illustrated in Fig. 4; for h > 20 nm, the beam and 2D models give nearly same values for f. However, when h ≤\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
